FINDING judge-002 (MEDIUM, verdict-binding, rule scope.existing-get-behavior-change):
The webhook-specific JSON-parse error handler is registered globally via app.use(), not scoped to /webhook, so it intercepts malformed-JSON bodies sent to ANY route including the pre-existing GET routes. A live GET /health probe with a malformed-JSON body and Content-Type: application/json returned 401 invalid_signature; baseline (pre-diff) behavior for the same request was Express's generic 400 HTML parse-error page. This changes observable behavior for existing GET routes, violating the spec's explicit Out of Scope constraint ("No changes to ... existing GET /health, GET /items, GET /items/:id behavior").

</verify_finding>

<task>
Scope ALL webhook-specific body-parsing behavior (raw-body capture via the `verify` option, and the JSON-parse-error-handling middleware) to the `/webhook` route ONLY, so existing GET routes are provably unaffected. Concretely:

1. Revert the top-level `app.use(express.json({ verify: ... }))` back to the ORIGINAL unmodified `app.use(express.json());` (no `verify` option at the app level — this is what existed before this feature; other routes never needed raw-body capture).
2. Create a webhook-scoped JSON parser: `const webhookJsonParser = express.json({ verify: (req, _res, buf) => { req.rawBody = buf; } });` (module-level, not mounted globally).
3. Create a webhook-scoped 4-arg error-handling middleware (same logic as the current global one — SyntaxError + entity.parse.failed → check signature via `hasValidSignature(req)` → 401 or 400) as its own named function, not mounted globally.
4. Register both as route-specific middleware on the `/webhook` route only: `app.post('/webhook', webhookJsonParser, webhookParseErrorHandler, (req, res) => { ... the existing handler body ... });` — Express supports a 4-arg (err-handling) middleware function within a single route's handler chain; it is only invoked when a preceding handler in that same chain calls `next(err)`, and Express's route dispatcher recognizes it by its arity the same way `app.use` does at the app level.
5. Do not change any other route's registration or the existing `app.get('/health', ...)`, `app.get('/items', ...)`, `app.get('/items/:id', ...)` handlers at all.

Add a regression test proving existing GET routes are unaffected: send a malformed-JSON body with `Content-Type: application/json` to `GET /health` (or another existing GET route) and assert the response is NOT the webhook's `{ error: 'invalid_signature' }` / `{ error: 'invalid_body' }` shape (Express's default behavior for an unhandled route-level JSON parse error on a GET route is its own concern — just assert it's NOT one of the two webhook-specific JSON error shapes, proving the webhook-specific handling didn't leak).

Keep all previously-fixed behavior intact: signature check ordering (bg-002/bg-003/bg-004), duplicate/replay handling (bg-001), and all 14 existing webhook tests must still pass unchanged in behavior (their `/webhook` requests still go through the same `webhookJsonParser` + `webhookParseErrorHandler` + `hasValidSignature` logic, just scoped to the route now instead of globally).
